Description
===========
       C++ source code example for AMD/Xilinx LogiCORE FFT.
       This example is a 1,024 pts FFT (SSR=2) with floating-point data that supports
       both ARRAY and STREAM interfaces through a compile-time macro.
       
       The USE_STREAM_INTERFACE macro in fft_top.h controls the interface type:
         - Set to 0 for ARRAY interface
         - Set to 1 for STREAM interface (default)
 
Interface Selection
===================
To change the interface type, modify the USE_STREAM_INTERFACE macro in fft_top.h:

For ARRAY interface:
    #define USE_STREAM_INTERFACE 0

For STREAM interface (default):
    #define USE_STREAM_INTERFACE 1

The testbench automatically adapts to the selected interface and prints
which interface is being used during simulation.

Files
=====
data/                  : Directory with test stimulus and expected FFT results for 5 test cases:
                         ramp, sine, sawtooth, mixed, and impulse signals
plots/                 : Directory containing visualization plots of FFT results
new_fft_tb.cpp         : C testbench that supports both ARRAY and STREAM interfaces
fft_top.cpp            : Top function fft_top with interface selection via macro
fft_top.h              : Header file with FFT parameters and interface selection macro
generate_fft_data.py   : Python script to generate test stimulus and expected FFT output files
plot_fft_data.py       : Python script to visualize time domain signals and FFT results
run.py                 : Script to run C simulation, C synthesis and co-simulation using Vitis
run_hls.tcl            : Script to run C simulation, C synthesis and co-simulation using Vitis
README                 : This readme file

Test Cases
==========
The testbench includes 5 comprehensive test cases:
1. Ramp        - Linear increase from 0 to 1023
2. Sine        - Pure sine wave at frequency bin 10
3. Sawtooth    - Periodic ramp (seesaw) with period 64
4. Mixed       - Combination of three sine waves at bins 10, 25, 50
5. Impulse     - Unit impulse at t=0

Generate Test Data
==================
To regenerate test stimulus and expected results:
    python3 generate_fft_data.py

This creates input signals and computes reference FFT outputs using NumPy.

Visualize Results
=================
To generate plots of test signals and FFT results:
    python3 plot_fft_data.py

This creates PNG plots in the plots/ directory showing time domain and frequency domain analysis.

Interface Comparison
====================
ARRAY Interface:
  - Simple array-based data passing
  - Suitable for block processing
  - Function signature: fft_top(bool direction, cmpxDataIn in[FFT_LENGTH], ...)

STREAM Interface:
  - Uses hls::stream for sequential data transfer
  - Better for pipelined streaming applications
  - Function signature: fft_top(bool dir, hls::stream<...> &in, ...)

Run Example
===========
1. Choose interface type by editing USE_STREAM_INTERFACE in fft_top.h
2. Run using Python script:
       vitis -s run.py
   Or use Tcl:
       vitis-run --mode hls --tcl run_hls.tcl

The testbench output will indicate which interface is being tested.